The paper proposes a framework for static analysis of programs that process data in files, which is a problem that is relevant to several sub-fields of computer science. However, the focus of the paper is on the use of file format specifications to improve the precision of static analysis, which suggests that the paper is most likely to belong to the Programming Languages (cs.PL) or Software Engineering (cs.SE) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper mentions the use of abstract interpretation, which is a technique commonly used in program analysis and verification, further supporting the likelihood of cs.PL and cs.SE. The paper also discusses the application of the proposed framework to real-world programs in domains such as banking and healthcare, which suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) and Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-categories. Finally, the paper presents empirical results using real and realistic programs, which suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
